caption: Authentic Spanish cuisine, amazing gin & tonics, thoughtful service.  All on Division Street, which is still awesome for people watching.
Food and cocktails are great. The staff is exceptional and made the birthday celebration very special. Would recommend to everyone!
The combination of service and ambience was phenomenal. Great aromas from the kitchen and excellent cocktails. May have found a new favorite in town.
On the web page they only mention an extra 3.5% charge to credit cards but nothing about debit. They should be clear regarding this matter cuz credit cards and debit cards are not the same thing.
Amazing concept and staff!
Mama Delia’s was a great experience. The outdoor ambiance, the servers expertise, and the FOOD. Highly recommend the squid ink paella. I haven’t had that good of paella since I lived in Barcelona!
The service and the food is 💯. I really enjoy the Bonhomme group of restaurants. Thank you for always creating a memorable experience.

Yum yum yum 😋 Everything was absolutely mouthwatering! The steak melted in my mouth and was beautifully seasoned! Every dish perfectly paired with wine! That cheesecake is the perfect blend of sweet and savory.
Service was unfriendly and slow. the only redeeming quality was their French fries. The food and drinks were outrageously expensive and-was $17 for a tequila. Don’t go here!
No Coors Lite; but great staff and clientele. Bathrooms are legit, too.

Missing my annual trip to Spain, stopped by based on recent reviews and enjoyed the food, patio ambiance and knowledgeable service. I always try octopus where ever I travel; the Pulpo Canario, very good but I prefer a bit more tender, the Papa con Chocolate is one of the best deserts I’ve had!
Expensive place
Octopus was amazing, bartender knew his wines! Wait staff was kind, professional and knowledgeable 😁 great atmosphere and thoughtful design
Went there for a friends birthday and the steak, the scallops, and the caviar was delicious I can’t wait to go back and have some more to try

4 stars, previously 5 and still a very good place to eat and have a drink. I can't figure out why they took away croquetas de jamon, making croquetas obligatorily a mix of jamon/mejillones. It was still ok, and everything else we had was good, but just seems like this place makes changes for the sake of change sometimes. And I have never seen ham mixed with mussels in a croquette, having been to Spain well over a dozen times, sometimes for months at a time.  I have seen one or the other, but never both in the same croquette. Prices have also gone up considerably over the years (well beyond inflation). And on top of that, they now have a 3.5 percent charge for using a credit card. Finally, the wines by the glass dont even include a Ribera del Duero option. Overall, still a solid spot for dinner... for now.  Hopefully they won't try to do "too much" with this place.  I don't think they realize that many people come here for solid, authentic tasting Spanish food.  If this place ever becomes a doppleganger of Porto, I won't be back.  I think Chef Marcos has a good concept with Porto, but this place should not become anything resembling porto or I fear Mama Delia will experience gradually increasing customer attrition. Don't forget your loyal Black Bull customer base. With that said, I look forward to my next meal here. I'm just not sure how much longer I can justify coming here if it ends up straying too far from its roots.  I used to recommend this to anyone looking for the BEST Spanish food in Chicago. It's becoming a harder sell every year although I still think it narrowly holds onto the title.
It was good. Octopus & scallops were great. I think it would've been better to sit inside.  Portions were small for the price. Shared plates. Had many plates, but still left hungry.
Food was brilliant and the service was terrific. We barely looked at the menu, it was more of a conversation and some guidance. Will be back many more times.

Ummm if you like to eat food this is not the place for you.. The more money you spend the less food you get. My husband recieve his food first and i waited 15min after him to get two scallops that was very expensive and nasty.. Seriously....a bill ober a hundred bucks for two people that you can finsh in less than 5min and waited over an hour to get... Never again

I've worked in Andalusian and basque restaurants and I promise you this is some of the best you can get.  Scallops,  pulpo, boquerones,  the cheeses,  paella... all fabulous! 5 stars.  Great pace of serving and careful in explaining the dishes,  both the food runners and Alyson.  Would wanna come back.  Anytime
Food is amazing, Cocktail program is impeccable and Service is great.   Pricy...but worth it
What a great experience! I was impressed. So many interesting and delicious dishes. My new favorite restaurant in Wicker Park.

I love the ambiance and our waitress had really good recommendations. The star dishes in my opinion are the octopus with potatoes, scallops with jamon, paella with shrimp, and the gin and tonics. My only recommendation is to include more veggie based dishes. For example, I love eggplant with honey or even a take on the spanish omlette would be nice. There absolutely needs to be Spanish olives and cheeses (manchego would be an easy one) to go with the jamon dishes. Finally, if this is truly tapas style, dishes need to be made to accommodate groups. The muffulata, for example, is cut in two. There were three of us and so we had to cut it up ourselves in order to share.

Being a local in the Wicker Park area I have to say it’s kind of heartbreaking to write this review ;( In the last eleven years, I’ve seen the change in the neighborhood from cute little  shops to top of the line restaurants and coffee bars in Chicago.  I consider Black Bull now Mama Delia on Division St the place to go for a drink or dinner after work… Or else, yeah! The  special spot in the city to bring your family and friends on a weekend gathering celebration. When I saw the restoration being done in June I said: Oh well… another of my favorites is closing…gone! Black Bull survived the tough years after the Great Recession, but not the pandemia. I am sad”. But hey!!! surprise! I heard… “No, it’s not totally gone, it’s just an upgrade, it’s same owner with a more fabulous Spanish menu, it has now a pink wall instead of the black facade and a pretty name. That’s all!“ I was relieved, I very much love the diversity in the area and the Spanish food brings enough to me. Here is the point, I liked Black Bull not only because of the menu, but because, it was very welcoming, very friendly, fantastic service and happy servers, the environment was excellent, the managing was caring and awesome even in the slowest days like on a Wednesday night. Now we have a very sophisticated place and suitable and appealing menu… good food for sure $$$$$$$ yikes! However, last night... Wednesday... my experience with Mama Delia was of a very unwelcoming staff, boring, sad, low energy… I say unhappy environment. Oh come on… Owner think of this… Where’s the inspiration now? You don’t brand a restaurant on a concept and ambiance only, you brand it mainly on your customer service and satisfaction. In other words, on customer happiness and loyalty. Last night, was probably not the night to visit you, but coming from work on a beautiful summer night and since you’re on my way home, I stopped by… but I wish I wouldn’t have done it, because, I found myself now taking the time to write this review. People, weekends are probably better to visit Mama Delia since during the week it may not be the best experience. I want to be fair, so I’d mention from my previous visits in July and August chef Antonio and mixologist Ricky are great ;) good customer care and satisfaction. At least someone cares!

The food waa amazing. We tried several dishes and each was delicious. The problem we had was with the host stand. We weren't seated until 30 minutes after our reservation, then no one came to our table for another 20 minutes. So basically an hour after our reservation we finally got our drink order taken. From then on it was great, but the delay but us in a bad mood for the rest of dinner.

Authentic Spanish food (from Spain) in Chicago! Fresh seafood and top quality ingredients, specially rice dishes, with black rice (from squid ink) as the top dish! Good cocktails, too.  Just be aware: the place is not cheap. Good quality requires cost, so don’t expect to pay less than 45-50$ each (group of 4-5 people) or 60-65$ (couples).
Great paella!!!!

You have to try the Vaca vieja! It's so succulent and tender, it's easily become my all time favorite dish! Don't get me started on their drinks. The best! To me at least, this place is like a piece of art. The dishes are amazing, the staff is stupendous and the atmosphere is super inviting, heck, even the aroma is enticing! I'm a fan, have been and will continue to be! <3
Best Spanish food in the city

We recently celebrated the anniversary of my birth this past weekend and could not have thought of a better place for dinner. The staff was wonderful. The service was outstanding. The food was phenomenal. 'Nuff said.

Kassy took our visit from a ‘dinner’ to an ‘experience’ - taking the time to thoughtfully explain the menu and suggest meaningful and intentional dishes. Absolutely impressed by unique dishes and want to come back asap, SO GOOD.

A must! Gorgeous space indoors and out, and with all-day hours and a menu that can flex from snacks and drinks to five course meal, you can make the experience follow your mood. The safety precautions for employees and staff make for a really comfortable dining experience.
